title: For Sale:  S.A.C.M. Model 1935A
postcontent:
It's in rough shape, but there's no rust.  I've never fired it.  Chambered for the 7.65mm Longue cartridge, the 1935A was used by the French military and police. Initial production began in 1937, and the pistol began delivery to the French Army in late 1939, with a total of about 10,700 pistols built before German forces occupied the SACM factory in the summer of 1940.  The French again produced it after the war.
The 7.65 x 20mm (or French long) cartridge is out of production and hard to find.  My research suggested that old ammo from WWII, if it even works, might be dangerous as some loads were sabotaged.

It shares the same competition-proven baffle stack as the 30BA and 30P-1 (with a few new optimizations), but we've designed a new brake that is smaller and more efficient than the old one.When used alone, the new "CB" brake is approx 30-40% more effective at recoil reduction than the old 30BA brake. The new brake is proportioned correctly for .223 and .30 caliber rifles, but it provides a suppressor mounting surface just as solid as the old 30BA series.The way to interpret the model number for the 30CB9 is: .30caliber, COMPACT BRAKE, 9-inch long (full size)The 30CBx series replaces the 30BA/BAS series as of May 2014. We will continue to sell 30BA series brakes and suppressors to existing "BA"-series customers if requested.The 30CB9 offers best-in-class sound suppression levels in a very light weight format, and is built with accuracy as its first priority. The 30CB9 is designed to mount over our new compact muzzle brake. It is particularly suited to applications where the rifle will be shot suppressed and unsuppressed, and a brake is desired when shooting without the suppressor.The "CB" series suppressors was designed to mount over our new compact brake and provide the same repeatability as our direct thread attach suppressors, like the 30P-1. The 30CB9 features a conical shoulder for rock solid POI repeatability and to make sure it never comes loose.The 30CB9 was designed around .308 for maximum flexibility and is rated up to .300 Winchester Magnum, but it's the ideal suppressor for the most competitive mid-sized cartridges for long-range shooting such as .243 Winchester .260 Remington, 6.5 Creedmoor, 6.5x47 Lapua, 6.5-284 Norma, and 7mm Remington Magnum & WSM.The 30CB9 uses the baffle stack of the 30P-1, which has racked up impressive results at long-range field shooting events in the Rocky Mountain region, including the Blue Steel Ranch Steel Safari and the NRA Whittington Center Sporting Rifle Match. Many long-range shooters prefer shooting suppressed because the muzzle blast and concussion is eliminated, while the recoil impulse is reduced and smoothed out over time. The net result is that the rifle is easier to shoot and it's easier to make hits. Communication with your spotter is easier because the need for hearing protection is reduced.The 30CB9 is constructed of titanium with a fully-welded baffle core. title: For Sale:  FN FAL G1 kit, parkerized
postcontent:
Excellent G1 kit with fresh manganese phosphate parkerizing. Kit is mostly 'correct' for a FN produced German contract rifle with the exceptions of the lever style gas plug, a Steyr gas piston (can be substituted for a US made piston), the short gas tube, the Imbel bolt, and the Belgian non trapdoor stock. No serial numbers match but bolt is unnumbered.  Kit features excellent handguards and bipods that are largely free of dings and have good screws and hardware, unground flashider with a NOS spring for a super tight and wiggle free fit, new DSA gas plug, soldered in short gas tube, new carry handle plastic, excellent ding free topcover, 1958 dated barrel with a good bore and a throat erosion of less than 0 on a brownells gauge, 1957 dated charging handle in excellent shape, new old stock steyr pistol grip, and fabulous non trapdoor cut Belgian type C walnut stock with great original buttplate.  Also has had a trigger job, and comes with three different weight hammer springs for the individual to experiment with.  The stock is the real prize, though.  Uncracked, very proud around the buttplate and ferrule, sharp contours.  Minor dings but no real damage at all, and would make a beautiful restoration project.  The gas tube is the soldered in short type, and it is not original to the barrel or gas block.  I opted to use that tube instead of the original longer non soldered type.  This tube is quite pitted on the outside but fine on the inside, however in hindsight I regret using it.  If you'd like I can remove it and clean the gas block up to use the original long tube, which I will of course include.  

I will ship this kit anywhere in the US, and shipping is included in the sale price.  I also build FAL rifles and do parkerizing (I put this kit together), so if you would like to have it built and finished out into a complete rifle we can talk about that.  Also, if you are not that fond of the wood stock, a plastic Steyr stock can be substituted for $100 less.  

No trades at this time, please.  MANY more detailed images, please email and ask for them.  

Thanks!
